I accomplish this with a simple backend. Not sure if it needs to be added to this module. 

`
from django.conf import settings
from django.contrib.auth.models import User


class EmailOrUsernameModelBackend(object):
    def authenticate(self, username=None, password=None):
        if username:
            if '@' in username:
                kwargs = {'email': username}
            else:
                kwargs = {'username': username}
            try:
                user = User.objects.get(**kwargs)
                if user.check_password(password):
                    return user
            except User.DoesNotExist:
                return None
                

    def get_user(self, user_id):
        try:
            return User.objects.get(pk=user_id)
        except User.DoesNotExist:
            return None
`

@ashwoods currunt  raven-aiohttp works exactly like fire and forget. Errors comes to logs via `failure_cb`. But if loop is full of tasks and application stopped users will see tons of asyncio errors like https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio-dev.html#asyncio-pending-task-destroyed 
Thats why explicit method close is added. Users can wait until all tasks done or just cancel them bypassing `timeout=0`

